@startuml mlx-thinking-mode
' DTA Brand: #0096FF, #1A1A1A, #AAAAAA, #FFFFFF

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 1.5
skinparam roundcorner 8
skinparam defaultFontColor #1A1A1A
skinparam sequenceParticipantBorderColor #0096FF
skinparam sequenceParticipantBackgroundColor #E8F4FF
skinparam sequenceLifeLineBorderColor #AAAAAA
skinparam noteBorderColor #0096FF
skinparam noteBackgroundColor #E8F4FF
skinparam sequenceDividerBackgroundColor #E8F4FF
skinparam sequenceDividerBorderColor #0096FF
skinparam sequenceArrowColor #1A1A1A

title <color:#0096FF>The Thinking Mode Trap: Raw Prompt vs Chat Template</color>

participant "Your Code" as code #E8F4FF
participant "Tokenizer" as tok #CCE9FF
participant "Qwen 3.5\nModel" as model #E8F4FF

== Wrong: Raw Prompt String ==

code -> model: <font color="#AAAAAA">prompt = "Describe a tavern..."</font>
model -> model: Thinking mode\ntriggers unpredictably
model -> code: <font color="#AAAAAA"><think>1. Analyze... 2. Brainstorm...</think></font>\n(reasoning dump, not prose)

note right of model
  Raw strings bypass the
  model's expected format.
  Output is unpredictable.
end note

== Correct: Chat Template ==

code -> tok: apply_chat_template(\n  messages=[...],\n  enable_thinking=**False**)
tok -> tok: Format with special\ntokens + system prompt
tok -> model: Properly formatted\nprompt with thinking disabled
model -> code: <font color="#0096FF">"The heavy oak doors of</font>\n<font color="#0096FF">The Gilded Tankard groan open..."</font>\n(structured prose)

note right of tok
  Always use the tokenizer.
  It knows the model's
  expected input format.
end note

@enduml
